rv_baremetal-boot-plan9-riscv64: first working Plan9 objtype=riscv64 bare-metal example, and the site of the -T base addressing bug fix

WHAT THIS IS
------------
The first riscv64 (`jc`/`ja`/`jl`) example to blink the LED using real
linked calls (PUT32/dummy) instead of rv_baremetal-boot-plan9-riscv's
inlined pointer-store workaround - objtype=riscv64 doesn't hit the
C.JAL/C.ADDIW collision that objtype=riscv (RV32) does, since RV64C has
no C.JAL encoding to collide on. GET32 is declared here but never
actually called from main.c - see rv_baremetal-boot-plan9-riscv64-func
for a dedicated test that also exercises GET32's return value; this
folder never fully proved the call/return convention on its own.

BUG FOUND AND FIXED HERE
-------------------------
The first build of this folder hung/showed a dark LED. Hand-decoding
the output showed `MOVW $stack+16384(SB), R2` and `MOVW $main(SB), R10`
both resolved to addresses missing the `-T 0x41000000` link base
entirely (R2 came out as 0x4000 instead of 0x410040A8-ish, R10 as
0x24 instead of 0x41000024) - nowhere near the D1's DRAM, so the board
crashed from its first few instructions.

Root cause: sys/src/cmd/il/optab.c's dispatch table routed
`AMOVW`+`C_LECON` (the operand shape for `MOVW $symbol(SB), Rd`) to
case-type 9 in asm.c, which computes the address from `regoff()` alone
and never adds `instoffx` (the INITTEXT/INITDAT base `aclass()` computes
separately). The near-identical `AMOV`+`C_LECON` row already pointed at
the correct case-type 20 (which does add `instoffx`, using PC-relative
AUIPC+ADDI for thechar=='j'). One-line fix: routed AMOVW to 20 as well,
matching AMOV's row. Confirmed by hand-decoding the rebuilt binary (R2
now correctly resolves to 0x410040A8, R10 to 0x41000024) and by LED
blink on real hardware. See the BinOutput project's memory:
plan9-riscv64-symbol-reloc-bug for the full diagnosis.

start.s's comments in this folder still read "UNVERIFIED" in a few
places (64-bit MOVW semantics, PUT32/GET32's register convention) -
that's the state of knowledge at the time this folder was written,
before the fixes/confirmations above and before
rv_baremetal-boot-plan9-riscv64-func fully proved the call convention.
Left as-is for history; later folders carry the corrected
understanding.

STATUS
------
Confirmed working on real hardware (LED blinks) after the optab.c fix.
Does not use MOVW $setSB(SB), R3 (see
rv_baremetal-boot-plan9-riscv64-uart's README and the
plan9-riscv-missing-setsb memory) - fine here since nothing in this
folder references a small global/string constant, only large MMIO
addresses and function symbols (always C_LECON regardless of size for
functions - see that memory for the distinction).

BUILD
-----
mk (produces main.out and main.bin; main.bin is the flashable headerless
output, built with -s to strip Plan9 symbols). objtype=riscv64 is set
at the top of the mkfile.
